% RESULTS
% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
% \clearpage
\section*{Results}
% Paragraph
Our dataset includes 11 deciduous tree species with leaf phenology data spanning nine years (2016 to 2024) for a total of 
\Sexpr{nrow(empfullsosts)} leafout and 
\Sexpr{nrow(empfulleosts)} leaf coloring
observations, yielding 
\Sexpr{nrow(empts)} complete growing seasons (GS) for 
\Sexpr{length(unique(empts$id))} individuals. Throughout the duration of the study, mean summer temperatures spanned 
\Sexpr{tsjja$tmeanmean[which.min(tsjja$tmeanmean)]}$^\circ$C 
(\Sexpr{tsjja$year[which.min(tsjja$tmeanmean)]}) to 
\Sexpr{tsjja$tmeanmean[which.max(tsjja$tmeanmean)]}$^\circ$C 
(\Sexpr{tsjja$year[which.max(tsjja$tmeanmean)]}), with an average of
\Sexpr{mean(tsjja$tmeanmean)}$^\circ$C. 2020 and 2022 had moderate droughts in the summer (June, July and August), which ramped up to severe in September. A moderate drought in June 2016, ramped up to severe in July, then extreme in August and September. 
%emw25Jun -- somewhere in the methods you should say how you checked these early seasons -- or maybe 77 is not really an outlier? Small issue we can fix with a git issue if you need help. 
The calendar season (GSL) ranged from 
\Sexpr{min(empts$pgsGSL)} days ({\Afla} in 
\Sexpr{empts$year[which.min(empts$pgsGSL)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(empts$pgsGSL)} days ({\Asac} in 
\Sexpr{empts$year[which.max(empts$pgsGSL)]}), while the thermal season (GDD) ranged from 
\Sexpr{round(min(empts$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Afla} in 
\Sexpr{empts$year[which.min(empts$pgsGDD5)]}) to 
\Sexpr{round(max(empts$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Tame} in 
\Sexpr{empts$year[which.max(empts$pgsGDD5)]}). The earliest start of season (leafout) was 
\Sexpr{empts$loCal[which.min(empts$leafout)]} ({\Afla} in 
\Sexpr{empts$year[which.min(empts$leafout)]}) and the latest, 
\Sexpr{empts$loCal[which.max(empts$leafout)]} ({\Cova} in 
\Sexpr{empts$year[which.max(empts$leafout)]}), while the earliest leaf coloring day of year was
\Sexpr{empts$clCal[which.min(empts$coloredLeaves)]} ({\Afla} in 
\Sexpr{empts$year[which.min(empts$coloredLeaves)]}---same individual with earliest leafout) and the latest, 
\Sexpr{empts$clCal[which.max(empts$coloredLeaves)]} ({\Tame} in
\Sexpr{empts$year[which.max(empts$coloredLeaves)]}). Annual ring widths across years varied from 
\Sexpr{min(empts$lengthMM)} mm ({\Asac} in \Sexpr{empts$year[which.min(empts$lengthMM)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(empts$lengthMM)} mm ({\Tame} in \Sexpr{empts$year[which.max(empts$lengthMM)]}) (Figure \ref{fig:tsboxplot}).

% Paragraph
Across our eleven species and season predictors, we did not find any clear response of the growing season length on growth. %emw25Jun -- 'effect' is stats, not biology, fix this when you make it full text
%emw25Jun -- all my comments on units (and $z$-score etc.) on wildcrokie apply here also -- I understand RW is easier for you, but I think mm/GSL or such may be easier for your audience; if you feel strongly though and or see this approach in lots of papers, let me know and I will let it go. 
We report estimates as means and 90\% uncertainty intervals (UI) that correspond to ring width change in mm on the log scale---henseforth "RW" per scaled predictor (see methods for details on predictor scaling).
Longer thermal season did not increase growth for any species and decreased growth for {\Ball}
(\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_gdd$mean[bspp_df2_ts_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis"]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_gdd$p5[bspp_df2_ts_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis"]},
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_gdd$p95[bspp_df2_ts_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis"]} $\Delta$ RW/scaled GDD; Figure \ref{fig:tsmuplotbspp}a and e; Table \ref{tab:ts_slope_table}). Longer calendar season did not change growth for any species (Figure \ref{fig:tsmuplotbspp}b and f; Table \ref{tab:ts_slope_table}). Finally, on a scaled axis ($z$-scored), both GDD and GSL were similarly predictive (Figure \ref{fig:bsppZscored})

% Paragraph
Previous year GDD increased growth for {\Ball}
(\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_prvs$mean[bspp_df2_ts_prvs$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis"]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_prvs$p5[bspp_df2_ts_prvs$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis"]},
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_prvs$p95[bspp_df2_ts_prvs$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis"]} $\Delta$ RW/scaled GDD),
and decreased growth for {\Bnig}
(\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_prvs$mean[bspp_df2_ts_prvs$spp_name %in% "B. nigra"]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_prvs$p5[bspp_df2_ts_prvs$spp_name %in% "B. nigra"]},
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_prvs$p95[bspp_df2_ts_prvs$spp_name %in% "B. nigra"]} $\Delta$ RW/scaled GDD; Figure \ref{fig:tsPrvsYr}b; Table \ref{tab:tab_PrvsYr})

Interestingly, {\Bnig} did not solely respond to current year's conditions (Figure \ref{fig:tsmuplotbspp}a and e; Table \ref{tab:ts_slope_table}), but grew more with warmer thermal season when the previous conditions were considered
(\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_curr$mean[bspp_df2_ts_curr$spp_name %in% "B. nigra"]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_curr$p5[bspp_df2_ts_curr$spp_name %in% "B. nigra"]},
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_curr$p95[bspp_df2_ts_curr$spp_name %in% "B. nigra"]} $\Delta$ RW/scaled GDD; Figure \ref{fig:tsPrvsYr}a; Table \ref{tab:tab_PrvsYr}).

% Paragraph
An earlier start of season did not increase growth for any species and decreased growth for {\Tame} (
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_sos$mean[bspp_df2_ts_sos$spp_name %in% "T. americana"]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_sos$p5[bspp_df2_ts_sos$spp_name %in% "T. americana"]},
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_sos$p95[bspp_df2_ts_sos$spp_name %in% "T. americana"]} $\Delta$ RW/scaled SOS; Figure \ref{fig:tsmuplotbspp}c and g; Table \ref{tab:ts_slope_table}), which did not respond to the thermal or the calendar season.

A later end of season did not increase growth for any species and decreased growth for {\Ball} (
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_eos$mean[bspp_df2_ts_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis"]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_eos$p5[bspp_df2_ts_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis"]},
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_eos$p95[bspp_df2_ts_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis"]} $\Delta$ RW/scaled EOS; Figure \ref{fig:tsmuplotbspp}d and h; Table \ref{tab:ts_slope_table}), which also decreased growth with warmer thermal season.

The estimates were unchanged when using the full or restricted datasets (SOS $n =$
\Sexpr{nrow(empfullsosts)} and EOS $n =$
\Sexpr{nrow(empfulleosts)} vs $n=$
\Sexpr{nrow(empts)}; Figure \ref{fig:tsSOSEOScomparison}b), or when using budburst instead of leafout as the start of the growing season (Figure \ref{fig:buburstVSleafoutTS}c).

A later SOS delayed EOS only for {\Pdel} 
(\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_co$mean[bspp_df2_ts_co$spp_name %in% "P. deltoides"]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_co$p5[bspp_df2_ts_co$spp_name %in% "P. deltoides"]},
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_ts_co$p95[bspp_df2_ts_co$spp_name %in% "P. deltoides"]} $\Delta$ EOS/SOS; Figure \ref{fig:SOSonEOS}


\subsection*{How did tree growth change across years and tree ids?}

We did not find any clear difference of growth across years (Figure \ref{fig:tsmuplotayear}; Table) and no clear differences of growth across species (Figure \ref{fig:tsxyGDDyr} and \ref{fig:tsxyGSLyr})

Growth was similar across individual trees (Figure \ref{fig:tsmuplotatreeid}).


% Figure mu across all species and climate predictors
\begin{figure}[!ht]
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{../../analyses/figures/growthModelsMain/TSmuALLbsppWlines.pdf}
\caption{Estimates of ring width change as a function of four different predictors (growing degree days, GDD (mean daily temperature above 5\degree C); growing season length, GSL; start of season, SOS; end of season, EOS) across our eleven species. The species colors are the same throughout the figures. Panels (a) to (d) represent the model slope estimates for each species, for each predictor, which we represent through ring width change on the log scale per seven average spring days GDD (\Sexpr{tsgddscale} GDD; panel a), seven days of GSL (panel b), seven days of leafout (SOS; panel c) and seven days of leaf colouring (EOS; panel d). The dots represent the mean of each species and the lines, the 50\% and 90\% uncertainty intervals (UI; see Table \ref{tab:ts_slope_table} for parameter estimates). Panels (e) to (h) represent the simulated response curves of ring width as a function of each predictor, with the lines depicting the mean response at each simulated predictor value, and the shaded area, the interquantile ranges (25\% and 75\% UI). These model do not include a slope on the previous year GDD (see Figure \ref{fig:tsPrvsYr} for these estimates).}
\label{fig:tsmuplotbspp}
\end{figure}

% Figure mu previous year and current year
\begin{figure}[!ht]
\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{../../analyses/figures/growthPreviousYearModel/bsppCurrentVSpreviousYR.jpeg}
\caption{Model slope estimates representing ring width change as a function of the current year growing degree days (GDD; a) and the previous year GDD (b). GDD represent the accumulated growing degree days between leafout and leaf colouring and the models estimates shows ring width change (on the log scale) per seven average spring days GDD (\Sexpr{tsgddscale}; see data analyses for more details).
The dots represent the mean of each species and the lines, the 50\% and 90\% uncertainty intervals (UI). }
\label{fig:tsPrvsYr}
\end{figure}

